{"1525–1591":"1525–1591","1525–1569":"1525–1569","1556–1644":"1556–1644","1559–Female":"1559–Deceased","1560–Female":"1560–Deceased","1562–1613":"1562–1613","1563–Male":"1563–Deceased","1565–1613":"1565–1613","1568–1613":"1568–1613","1500–1587":"1500–1587","26 Sep 1569":"26 September 1569","1560":"1560","1591":"1591","1525":"1525","1613":"1613","1569":"1569","1568":"1568","1556":"1556","1644":"1644","1500":"1500","1565":"1565","1587":"1587","1563":"1563","1562":"1562","01 FEB 1549":"1 February 1549","1559":"1559","England":"England, United Kingdom","Old Alresford,Hampshire,England":"Old Alresford, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England","London, England":"London, England","Ewell, Kent, England":"Ewell Manor, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Colchester, Essex, , England":"Colchester, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Colchester, Essex, England":"Colchester, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wayer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from an Anglo-Norman French variant of <i>gaugeor</i> ‘gauger (official who measured liquids)’, or of <i>gag(e)ure</i> ‘bet, wager’. Compare   Gager  , though the evidence for that suggests more strongly an occupational name.","German (also <b>Wäger</b>), Swiss German, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from Middle High German <i>wæger</i> ‘weigher’, German <i>Waager</i>, an occupational name for an official in charge of the city scales, responsible for weighing produce, especially produce offered as rent in kind, or for an official in charge of checking weights and measures used by merchants."],"variants":[{"name":"Wagemann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Heinrich, Kurt.","German: occupational name for an inspector of weights and measures (see   Wager  ). Compare   Wagaman  ,   Wageman  , and   Wogoman  ."]},{"name":"Wagers","meanings":["English and German: variant of   Wager  ."]},{"name":"Wagar","meanings":["Altered form of German   Wager  ."]},{"name":"Gager","meanings":["English (Essex, Surrey): occupational name from Middle English, Old French <i>gauger</i> (Anglo-Norman French <i>gaugeour</i>) ‘one who measures or gauges’, specifically an exciseman who measured the depth of wine in barrels.","English: possibly a variant of   Wager  .","German: probably a topographic name from Tyrolean <i>Gagen</i> ‘alpine dairy hut’."]},{"name":"Weger","meanings":["German: variant of <b>Wäger</b> (see   Wager  )."]}]},{"name":"Margret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margret Wayer was born in 1525, in England, United Kingdom as the daughter of William Thomas Wayer II. She married William Marsse on 1 February 1549, in Old Alresford, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 3 daughters. She died in 1591, in her hometown, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1525–1591":"1525–1591","1525–1569":"1525–1569","1556–1644":"1556–1644","1559–Female":"1559–Surnud","1560–Female":"1560–Surnud","1562–1613":"1562–1613","1563–Male":"1563–Surnud","1565–1613":"1565–1613","1568–1613":"1568–1613","1500–1587":"1500–1587","26 Sep 1569":"26. september 1569","1560":"1560","1591":"1591","1525":"1525","1613":"1613","1569":"1569","1568":"1568","1556":"1556","1644":"1644","1500":"1500","1565":"1565","1587":"1587","1563":"1563","1562":"1562","01 FEB 1549":"1. veebruar 1549","1559":"1559","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Old Alresford,Hampshire,England":"Old Alresford, Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England","London, England":"London, England","Ewell, Kent, England":"Ewell Manor, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Colchester, Essex, , England":"Colc